{"title_page": "Bhag Corona", "text_new": "'''Bhag Corona''' is an online browser game created by independent developers. The protagonist is the Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and the objective of the game is to shoot the COVID virus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mukherjee|first=Raka|url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/a-new-game-called-bhag-corona-helps-you-kill-coronavirus-with-pm-modi-2560989.html|title=A New Game Called 'Bhag Corona' Helps You 'Kill' Coronavirus With PM Modi|date=2 April 2020|work=News18|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The gameplay is simple and draws inspiration from the 2013 video game [[Flappy Bird]]. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Ghosh|first=Shreesha|url=https://www.edexlive.com/happening/2020/mar/31/bhag-corona-why-you-should-check-this-game-created-by-xlri-students-featuring-modi-shooting-vaccine-at-a-virus-11002.html|title=Bhag Corona: Why this game created by XLRI students featuring PM Modi shooting vaccine at a virus is a great stressbuster|date=31 March 2020|work=Edex Live|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The background score features 'Go Corona, Corona Go' chant attributed to Indian Union Minister [[Ramdas Athawale]]. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Ansari|first=Danish|url=https://www.republicworld.com/technology-news/gaming/what-is-bhag-corona-and-how-you-can-play-it.html|title=What Is Bhag Corona And How Can You Play It On Your Web Browser?|date=31 March 2020|work=Republic World|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The game displays personal hygiene educational messages when the character misses to hit the virus. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Dash|first=Sanchita|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/mba-students-built-a-game-bhag-corona-where-pm-modi-shoots-vaccines-at-coronavirus/articleshow/74943559.cms|title=These MBA students built a game \u2013 Bhag Corona where PM Modi shoots vaccines at coronavirus|date=2 April 2020|work=Business Insider|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was developed during the 21-day lockdown announced in India on 25th March, 2020. <ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=Shreya|url=https://news.careers360.com/bhag-corona-xlri-students-develop-educational-online-game|title=Bhag Corona: XLRI students develop an educational online game|date=30 March 2020|work=Careers360|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Archana|first=KC|url=https://www.indiatimes.com/trending/social-relevance/bhag-corona-coronavirus-awareness-web-game-509904.html|title=Bored? This Oddly Satisfying Game Called 'Bhag Corona' Will Help You Beat Isolation Blues|date=2 April 2020|work=IndiaTimes|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{uncategorised|date=April 2020}}{{stub}}\n", "text_old": "Bhag Corona is an online browser game created by independent developers. The protagonist is the Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and the objective of the game is to shoot the COVID virus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mukherjee|first=Raka|url=https://www.news18.com/news/buzz/a-new-game-called-bhag-corona-helps-you-kill-coronavirus-with-pm-modi-2560989.html|title=A New Game Called 'Bhag Corona' Helps You 'Kill' Coronavirus With PM Modi|date=2 April 2020|work=News18|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The gameplay is simple and draws inspiration from the 2013 video game [[Flappy Bird]]. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Ghosh|first=Shreesha|url=https://www.edexlive.com/happening/2020/mar/31/bhag-corona-why-you-should-check-this-game-created-by-xlri-students-featuring-modi-shooting-vaccine-at-a-virus-11002.html|title=Bhag Corona: Why this game created by XLRI students featuring PM Modi shooting vaccine at a virus is a great stressbuster|date=31 March 2020|work=Edex Live|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The background score features 'Go Corona, Corona Go' chant attributed to Indian Union Minister [[Ramdas Athawale]]. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Ansari|first=Danish|url=https://www.republicworld.com/technology-news/gaming/what-is-bhag-corona-and-how-you-can-play-it.html|title=What Is Bhag Corona And How Can You Play It On Your Web Browser?|date=31 March 2020|work=Republic World|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The game displays personal hygiene educational messages when the character misses to hit the virus. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Dash|first=Sanchita|url=https://www.businessinsider.in/india/news/mba-students-built-a-game-bhag-corona-where-pm-modi-shoots-vaccines-at-coronavirus/articleshow/74943559.cms|title=These MBA students built a game \u2013 Bhag Corona where PM Modi shoots vaccines at coronavirus|date=2 April 2020|work=Business Insider|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The game was developed during the 21-day lockdown announced in India on 25th March, 2020. <ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=Shreya|url=https://news.careers360.com/bhag-corona-xlri-students-develop-educational-online-game|title=Bhag Corona: XLRI students develop an educational online game|date=30 March 2020|work=Careers360|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Archana|first=KC|url=https://www.indiatimes.com/trending/social-relevance/bhag-corona-coronavirus-awareness-web-game-509904.html|title=Bored? This Oddly Satisfying Game Called 'Bhag Corona' Will Help You Beat Isolation Blues|date=2 April 2020|work=IndiaTimes|access-date=2 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{uncategorised|date=April 2020}}{{stub}}\n", "name_user": "Clovermoss", "label": "safe", "comment": "Bolded article title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhag_Corona"}
{"title_page": "H. Jack Geiger", "text_new": "{{short description|American physician}}\n{{quote box|align=right|width=33%|quote = The last time I checked my textbooks the specific therapy for malnutrition was, in fact, food.|Dr. Jack Geiger, 1965}}\n\n'''H. Jack Geiger''', MD, MSciHyg,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rwjf.org/en/errors/404.html|title=Page Not Found|website=RWJF|access-date=2019-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916063610/https://www.rwjf.org/en/errors/404.html|archive-date=2019-09-16|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://ajph.aphapublications.org/doi/full/10.2105/AJPH.92.11.1713|title=Community-Oriented Primary Care: A Path to Community Development|first=H. Jack|last=Geiger|date=1 November 2002|publisher=|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=92|issue=11|pages=1713\u20131716|via=ajph.aphapublications.org (Atypon)|doi=10.2105/AJPH.92.11.1713|pmc=3221474}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/thinktank/transcript931.html|title=PBS: Think Tank: Transcript for \"Has Medicine Gone PC?\"|website=www.pbs.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/exhibition/againsttheodds/podcast/geiger.html|title=Against The Odds:Making a Difference in Global Health|website=www.nlm.nih.gov}}</ref> (born 1926)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/gooddoctorsmedic00ditt|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/gooddoctorsmedic00ditt/page/63 63]|title=The Good Doctors: The Medical Committee for Human Rights and the Struggle for Social Justice in Health Care|first=John|last=Dittmer|date=1 July 2009|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> is a founding member and past president of [[Physicians for Human Rights]], a founding member and past president of [[Physicians for Social Responsibility]], a founding member and past president of the Committee for Health in South Africa, and a founding member and national program coordinator of the [[Medical Committee for Human Rights]].<ref name=\"physiciansforhumanrights.org\">{{cite web|url=http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/about/board_bios/jack-geiger.html|title=Physicians for Human Rights|publisher=|access-date=2009-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629173114/http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/about/board_bios/jack-geiger.html|archive-date=2010-06-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGeiger has led or participated in human rights missions for PHR, the United Nations, and the American Association for the Advancement of Science to former Yugoslavia, Iraq and Kurdistan, the West Bank and Gaza Strip, and South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/exhibition/againsttheodds/exhibit/community_health/common_ground.html|title=Against The Odds:Downloads > Audio Tour|website=www.nlm.nih.gov}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cfah.org/activities/geiger.cfm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211052113/http://www.cfah.org/activities/geiger.cfm |archive-date=2010-02-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Most of his professional career has been focused on the related issues of health, poverty, and civil rights.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.publichealthheroes.org/heroes/2001/geiger.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101209064856/http://www.publichealthheroes.org/heroes/2001/geiger.html |archive-date=2010-12-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.facesofhopecampaign.org/video_geiger.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091120145918/http://www.facesofhopecampaign.org/video_geiger.html |archive-date=2009-11-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Geiger initiated the community health center model in the United States, founding and directing the nation's inaugural community health centers, the first in Columbia Point, Boston (1965) and the second in the Mississippi Delta (1966). These centers became models for what is now a national network of more than 1100 CHCs serving some 20 million low-income and minority patients.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blog.sph.unc.edu/monday_morning/2008/09/16/heroes-and-celebrations/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610024416/http://blog.sph.unc.edu/monday_morning/2008/09/16/heroes-and-celebrations/ |archive-date=2010-06-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sph.unc.edu/health_behavior_and_health_education_news/department_hosts_second_retrospective_9034_8289.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617230545/http://www.sph.unc.edu/health_behavior_and_health_education_news/department_hosts_second_retrospective_9034_8289.html |archive-date=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nGeiger is a member of the [[Institute of Medicine]], [[United States National Academy of Sciences]], and the recipient of the IOM's highest honor, the Lienhardt Award for \"outstanding contributions to minority health.\"<ref name=\"physiciansforhumanrights.org\"/> In recognition of his work on racial and ethnic discrimination in health care, the Congressional Black, Hispanic and Asian American Caucuses have created the H. Jack Geiger Congressional Fellowships on Health Disparities for young minority scholars. In 2014, Geiger was awarded the [[Frank A. Calderone Prize]] by [[Columbia University Mailman School of Public Health|Columbia University's Mailman School of Public Health.]] \n\nGeiger is currently Professor Emeritus at the [[CUNY School of Medicine]] in New York City where he was a medical professor for many years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.ccny.cuny.edu/prospective/med/faculty/hgeiger.cfm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-11-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120910234906/http://www1.ccny.cuny.edu/prospective/med/faculty/hgeiger.cfm |archive-date=2012-09-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nGeiger began his career as a science journalist, where he was active in efforts to use science primarily in the service of human needs.<ref>Lewenstein, Bruce V. (1987). 'Public Understanding of Science' in America, 1945\u20131965.  Ph.D. dissertation, University of Pennsylvania, p. 234</ref> Geiger received his M.D. degree from [[Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine]] in 1958.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gwumc.edu/sphhs/departments/healthpolicy/ggprogram/geiger.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-04-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517205602/http://www.gwumc.edu/sphhs/departments/healthpolicy/ggprogram/geiger.cfm |archivedate=2012-05-17 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.case.edu/bulletin/09-11/medicine_general.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013011832/http://www.case.edu/bulletin/09-11/medicine_general.htm |archive-date=2009-10-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He then trained in internal medicine on the Harvard Service of Boston City Hospital from 1958\u201364. During this period he also earned a degree in epidemiology from the [[Harvard School of Public Health]], and was a Research Fellow, Research Training Program in Social Science and Medicine, [[Harvard University]].\n\n==Relationship with actor Canada Lee==\n[[Canada Lee]] met and was an influence on H. Jack Geiger, founder of Physicians for Social Responsibility. They met in 1940, when Geiger, a 14-year-old middle-class [[Jewish]] runaway, was backstage at a Broadway production of ''[[Native Son (play)|Native Son]]''. Lee agreed to take Geiger in when he showed up at his door in Harlem asking for a place to stay. Geiger stayed with Lee for over a year (with the consent of Geiger's parents), and Lee took on the role of surrogate father. During his time with Lee, Geiger was introduced to people like [[Langston Hughes]], [[Billy Strayhorn]], [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]], and [[Adam Clayton Powell Jr.|Adam Clayton Powell]]. After many years of varied experiences and an ongoing friendship with Lee, Geiger eventually became a journalist, then a doctor.\n\nThis event was recorded in an interview given by Jack Geiger on ''[[This American Life]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Geiger, H. Jack}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard School of Public Health alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Fellows]]\n[[Category:Jewish activists]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American physician}}\n{{quote box|align=right|width=33%|quote = The last time I checked my textbooks the specific therapy for malnutrition was, in fact, food.|Dr. Jack Geiger, 1965}}\n\n'''H. Jack Geiger''', MD, MSciHyg,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rwjf.org/en/errors/404.html|title=Page Not Found|website=RWJF|access-date=2019-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190916063610/https://www.rwjf.org/en/errors/404.html|archive-date=2019-09-16|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://ajph.aphapublications.org/doi/full/10.2105/AJPH.92.11.1713|title=Community-Oriented Primary Care: A Path to Community Development|first=H. Jack|last=Geiger|date=1 November 2002|publisher=|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=92|issue=11|pages=1713\u20131716|via=ajph.aphapublications.org (Atypon)|doi=10.2105/AJPH.92.11.1713|pmc=3221474}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/thinktank/transcript931.html|title=PBS: Think Tank: Transcript for \"Has Medicine Gone PC?\"|website=www.pbs.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/exhibition/againsttheodds/podcast/geiger.html|title=Against The Odds:Making a Difference in Global Health|website=www.nlm.nih.gov}}</ref> (born 1926)<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/gooddoctorsmedic00ditt|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/gooddoctorsmedic00ditt/page/63 63]|title=The Good Doctors: The Medical Committee for Human Rights and the Struggle for Social Justice in Health Care|first=John|last=Dittmer|date=1 July 2009|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA|via=Internet Archive}}</ref> is a founding member and past president of [[Physicians for Human Rights]], a founding member and past president of [[Physicians for Social Responsibility]], a founding member and past president of the Committee for Health in South Africa, and a founding member and national program coordinator of the [[Medical Committee for Human Rights]].<ref name=\"physiciansforhumanrights.org\">{{cite web|url=http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/about/board_bios/jack-geiger.html|title=Physicians for Human Rights|publisher=|access-date=2009-11-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629173114/http://physiciansforhumanrights.org/about/board_bios/jack-geiger.html|archive-date=2010-06-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nGeiger has led or participated in human rights missions for PHR, the United Nations, and the American Association for the Advancement of Science to former Yugoslavia, Iraq and Kurdistan, the West Bank and Gaza Strip, and South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/exhibition/againsttheodds/exhibit/community_health/common_ground.html|title=Against The Odds:Downloads > Audio Tour|website=www.nlm.nih.gov}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cfah.org/activities/geiger.cfm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211052113/http://www.cfah.org/activities/geiger.cfm |archive-date=2010-02-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Most of his professional career has been focused on the related issues of health, poverty, and civil rights.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.publichealthheroes.org/heroes/2001/geiger.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101209064856/http://www.publichealthheroes.org/heroes/2001/geiger.html |archive-date=2010-12-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.facesofhopecampaign.org/video_geiger.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091120145918/http://www.facesofhopecampaign.org/video_geiger.html |archive-date=2009-11-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Geiger initiated the community health center model in the United States, founding and directing the nation's inaugural community health centers, the first in Columbia Point, Boston (1965) and the second in the Mississippi Delta (1966). These centers became models for what is now a national network of more than 1100 CHCs serving some 20 million low-income and minority patients.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blog.sph.unc.edu/monday_morning/2008/09/16/heroes-and-celebrations/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100610024416/http://blog.sph.unc.edu/monday_morning/2008/09/16/heroes-and-celebrations/ |archive-date=2010-06-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sph.unc.edu/health_behavior_and_health_education_news/department_hosts_second_retrospective_9034_8289.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100617230545/http://www.sph.unc.edu/health_behavior_and_health_education_news/department_hosts_second_retrospective_9034_8289.html |archive-date=2010-06-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nGeiger is a member of the [[Institute of Medicine]], [[United States National Academy of Sciences]], and the recipient of the IOM's highest honor, the Lienhardt Award for \"outstanding contributions to minority health.\"<ref name=\"physiciansforhumanrights.org\"/> In recognition of his work on racial and ethnic discrimination in health care, the Congressional Black, Hispanic and Asian American Caucuses have created the H. Jack Geiger Congressional Fellowships on Health Disparities for young minority scholars.\n\nGeiger is currently Professor Emeritus at the [[CUNY School of Medicine]] in New York City where he was a medical professor for many years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.ccny.cuny.edu/prospective/med/faculty/hgeiger.cfm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-11-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120910234906/http://www1.ccny.cuny.edu/prospective/med/faculty/hgeiger.cfm |archive-date=2012-09-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nGeiger began his career as a science journalist, where he was active in efforts to use science primarily in the service of human needs.<ref>Lewenstein, Bruce V. (1987). 'Public Understanding of Science' in America, 1945\u20131965.  Ph.D. dissertation, University of Pennsylvania, p. 234</ref> Geiger received his M.D. degree from [[Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine]] in 1958.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gwumc.edu/sphhs/departments/healthpolicy/ggprogram/geiger.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-04-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120517205602/http://www.gwumc.edu/sphhs/departments/healthpolicy/ggprogram/geiger.cfm |archivedate=2012-05-17 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.case.edu/bulletin/09-11/medicine_general.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2009-11-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013011832/http://www.case.edu/bulletin/09-11/medicine_general.htm |archive-date=2009-10-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He then trained in internal medicine on the Harvard Service of Boston City Hospital from 1958\u201364. During this period he also earned a degree in epidemiology from the [[Harvard School of Public Health]], and was a Research Fellow, Research Training Program in Social Science and Medicine, [[Harvard University]].\n\n==Relationship with actor Canada Lee==\n[[Canada Lee]] met and was an influence on H. Jack Geiger, founder of Physicians for Social Responsibility. They met in 1940, when Geiger, a 14-year-old middle-class [[Jewish]] runaway, was backstage at a Broadway production of ''[[Native Son (play)|Native Son]]''. Lee agreed to take Geiger in when he showed up at his door in Harlem asking for a place to stay. Geiger stayed with Lee for over a year (with the consent of Geiger's parents), and Lee took on the role of surrogate father. During his time with Lee, Geiger was introduced to people like [[Langston Hughes]], [[Billy Strayhorn]], [[Richard Wright (author)|Richard Wright]], and [[Adam Clayton Powell Jr.|Adam Clayton Powell]]. After many years of varied experiences and an ongoing friendship with Lee, Geiger eventually became a journalist, then a doctor.\n\nThis event was recorded in an interview given by Jack Geiger on ''[[This American Life]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Geiger, H. Jack}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American activists]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:American epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:Case Western Reserve University School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard School of Public Health alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Fellows]]\n[[Category:Jewish activists]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n", "name_user": "MSPH Wiki", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added Frank Calderone Prize)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H._Jack_Geiger"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Ongoing viral pandemic in Italy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy\n| map1            = COVID-19 outbreak Italy per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1         = Confirmed cases per million inhabitants by province\n| map2            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Italy (Density).svg\n| legend2         = Number of confirmed cases by province<br>(as of 28 March): {{legend|#F2A88D|10\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#E36654|100\u2013499 confirmed}}{{legend|#E5354B|500\u2013999 confirmed}}{{legend|#87353F|1,000\u20139,999 confirmed}}{{legend|#630606|\u226510,000 confirmed}}\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = Italy\n| first_case      = [[Rome]]\n| arrival_date    = 31 January 2020<br/>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=31|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| first_outbreak  = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| index_case      = ''unknown''\n| deaths          = 13,915<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 18,278<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\"/> {{small|(incl. dismissed)}}\n| severe_cases    = 4,053<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\"/>\n| active_cases    = 83,049<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 115,252<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|http://www.salute.gov.it/nuovocoronavirus}}\n}}\n\nAn ongoing [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] ({{nowrap|COVID-19}}), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus&nbsp;2]] ({{nowrap|SARS-CoV-2}}), was first confirmed to have spread to [[Italy]] on 31 January 2020, when two Chinese tourists in [[Rome]] tested positive for the virus.<ref name=\"Corriere_20Jan\">{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Primi due casi in Italia|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_gennaio_30/coronavirus-italia-corona-9d6dc436-4343-11ea-bdc8-faf1f56f19b7.shtml |website=Corriere della sera |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=31 January 2020|language=it}}</ref> One week later an Italian man repatriated back to Italy from the city of [[Wuhan]], China, was hospitalised and confirmed as the third case in Italy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy-idUSKBN20F0UI|title=First Italian dies of coronavirus as outbreak flares in north|date=2020-02-21|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-03-06|language=en}}</ref> A cluster of cases was later detected, starting with 16 confirmed cases in [[Lombardy]] on 21 February,<ref name=\"ThomReut_IT_16cluster_21Feb\">{{cite news | last1= Anzolin | first1= Elisa | last2= Amante | first2= Angelo | title= Coronavirus outbreak grows in northern Italy, 16 cases reported in one day | date=21 February 2020 | agency=[[Thomson Reuters]] | url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy/coronavirus-outbreak-grows-in-northern-italy-16-cases-reported-in-one-day-idUSKBN20F0UI |accessdate=21 February 2020 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20200221225322/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-italy/coronavirus-outbreak-grows-in-northern-italy-16-cases-reported-in-one-day-idUSKBN20F0UI |archivedate= 21 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> and 60 additional cases and the first deaths on 22 February.<ref name=\"CorrieredSera_76_recent_cases\" /> By the beginning of March, the virus had spread to all regions of Italy.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus. Colpite tutte le regioni. La Protezione civile: ecco i numeri aggiornati |url=https://www.avvenire.it/attualita/pagine/coronavirus-aggiornamento-5-marzo-2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=www.avvenire.it |date=5 March 2020 |language=it}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, the Italian government suspended all flights to and from China and declared a state of emergency. In February, eleven municipalities in [[northern Italy]] were identified as the centres of the two main Italian clusters and placed under quarantine. The majority of positive cases in other regions traced back to these two clusters.<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/22/news/coronavirus_in_italia_aggiornamento_ora_per_ora-249241616/|title=Coronavirus in Italia: aggiornamento ora per ora|date=2020-02-22|website=la Repubblica|language=it|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> On 8 March 2020, [[Prime Minister of Italy|Prime Minister]] [[Giuseppe Conte]] expanded the quarantine to all of Lombardy and 14 other northern provinces, and on the following day to all of Italy, [[2020 Italy coronavirus lockdown|placing more than 60 million people in quarantine]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Northern Italy quarantines 16 million people |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51787238 |website=BBC |accessdate=8 March 2020 |date=8 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |title=All of Italy to be placed on coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-51810673 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=9 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-italy-sees-largest-daily-rise-in-deaths-and-confirmed-cases-11953192|title=Coronavirus: Italy deaths jump to 463, with 300 in just one region|website=Sky News|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> On 11 March 2020, Conte prohibited nearly all commercial activity except for supermarkets and pharmacies.<ref name=\":12\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/merkel-coronavirus-germany/2020/03/11/e276252a-6399-11ea-8a8e-5c5336b32760_story.html|title=Italy ramps up coronavirus lockdown, Merkel warns virus could infect two-thirds of Germany|last=Harlan|first=Chico|last2=Morris|first2=Loveday|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|last=Rome|first=Eric Sylvers in Milan and Giovanni Legorano in|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/italy-hardens-nationwide-quarantine-11583962093|title=Italy Hardens Nationwide Quarantine|date=2020-03-12|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-03-12|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> On 21 March, the Italian government closed all non-essential businesses and industries, with additional restrictions to movement of people.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Safi |first1=Michael |last2=Giuffrida |first2=Angela |last3=Farrer |first3=Martin |title=Coronavirus: Italy bans any movement inside country as toll nears 5,500 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/22/italian-pm-warns-of-worst-crisis-since-ww2-as-coronavirus-deaths-leap-by-almost-800 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 March 2020, the Italian College of Anesthesia, Analgesia, Resuscitation and Intensive Care (SIAARTI) published [[medical ethics]] recommendations regarding [[triage]] protocols that might be employed.<ref>{{cite techreport|url=http://www.siaarti.it/SiteAssets/News/COVID19%20-%20documenti%20SIAARTI/SIAARTI%20-%20Covid19%20-%20Raccomandazioni%20di%20etica%20clinica.pdf|title=Raccomandazioni di etica clinica per l\u2019ammissione a trattamenti intensivi e per la loro sospensione, in condizioni eccezionali di squilibrio tra necessit\u00e0 e risorse disponibili|institution=Italian College of Anesthesia, Analgesia, Resuscitation and Intensive Care (SIAARTI)|language=it|date=6 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|url-status=live|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312202813/http://www.siaarti.it/SiteAssets/News/COVID19%20-%20documenti%20SIAARTI/SIAARTI%20-%20Covid19%20-%20Raccomandazioni%20di%20etica%20clinica.pdf|archive-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/03/who-gets-hospital-bed/607807/|title=The Extraordinary Decisions Facing Italian Doctors|last=Mounk|first=Yascha|date=11 March 2020|work=[[The Atlantic]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233745/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2020/03/who-gets-hospital-bed/607807/|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|quote=Now the Italian College of Anesthesia, Analgesia, Resuscitation and Intensive Care (SIAARTI) has published guidelines for the criteria that doctors and nurses should follow in these extraordinary circumstances. The document begins by likening the moral choices facing Italian doctors to the forms of wartime triage that are required in the field of \"catastrophe medicine.\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-italy-doctors-tough-calls-survival/|title=Italian doctors on coronavirus frontline face tough calls on whom to save|last=Privitera|first=Greta|date=11 March 2020|work=[[Politico]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312125640/https://www.politico.eu/article/coronavirus-italy-doctors-tough-calls-survival/|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=12 March 2020|quote=\u2026the Italian Society of Anesthesia, Analgesia, Resuscitation and Intensive Care, who co-authored new guidelines on how to prioritize treatment of coronavirus cases in hospitals\u2026}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2020|04|02}}, Italy is one of the world's centres of active coronavirus cases with 83,049 active cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gisanddata.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6|title=Coronavirus COVID-19 Global Cases by the Center for Systems Science and Engineering (CSSE) at Johns Hopkins |access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The total of confirmed cases is 115,242, with 13,915 deaths, and 18,278 recoveries or dismissals.<ref name=\"Min_Salute_Situazione\">{{cite web|url=http://www.salute.gov.it/portale/nuovocoronavirus/dettaglioContenutiNuovoCoronavirus.jsp?lingua=italiano&id=5351&area=nuovoCoronavirus&menu=vuoto|title=Covid-19 \u2013 Situazione in Italia|website=www.salute.gov.it|publisher=Ministero della Salute|language=it|accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> By 2 April, Italy had conducted about 581,200 tests for the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salute.gov.it/imgs/C_17_pagineAree_5351_26_file.pdf|title=AGGIORNAMENTO 21/03/2020 ORE 17.00|date=21 March 2020|url-status=live|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> Due to the finite number of tests performed, the real number of infected people in Italy, as in other countries, is estimated to be higher than the official count.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Flaxman |first1=Seth |last2=Swapnil |first2=Mishra |last3=Gandy |first3=Axel |display-authors=etal |title=Report 13: Estimating the number of infections and the impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions on COVID-19 in 11 European countries |date=30 March 2020 |pages=1\u201335 |doi=10.25561/77731 |url=https://spiral.imperial.ac.uk:8443/handle/10044/1/77731 |accessdate=31 March 2020 |publisher=Imperial College London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Lau |first=Hien |last2=Khosrawipour |first2=Veria |last3=Kocbach |first3=Piotr |last4=Mikolajczyk |first4=Agata |last5=Ichii |first5=Hirohito |last6=Schubert |first6=Justyna |last7=Bania |first7=Jacek |last8=Khosrawipour |first8=Tanja |date=2020-03-14 |title=Internationally lost COVID-19 cases |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1684118220300736 |journal=Journal of Microbiology, Immunology and Infection |language=en |doi=10.1016/j.jmii.2020.03.013 |issn=1684-1182}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The total number of Italian coronavirus cases could be '10 times higher' than known tally, according to one official |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/24/italian-coronavirus-cases-seen-10-times-higher-than-official-tally.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> On 19 March, Italy became the country with the highest number of confirmed deaths in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2020/03/19/coronavirus-italy-now-has-more-covid-19-deaths-than-china/2873835001/|title=Grim milestone: Italy's coronavirus deaths surpass China's|first=Eric J. Lyman and Kim|last=Hjelmgaard|website=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nOn 31 December 2019, the Health Commission of [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]], informed the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] about a cluster of acute pneumonia cases with unknown origin in its province. On 9 January 2020, the [[Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CCDC) reported the identification of a [[novel coronavirus]] (later identified as the [[SARS-CoV-2]]) as the cause.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19 - Situazione nel mondo |url=http://www.salute.gov.it/portale/nuovocoronavirus/dettaglioContenutiNuovoCoronavirus.jsp?lingua=italiano&id=5338&area=nuovoCoronavirus&menu=vuoto |website=www.salute.gov.it |accessdate=4 March 2020 |language=IT}}</ref> In late January 2020, following the [[Mainland China during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak|developments of COVID-19 outbreak in mainland China]], on 3 February, Italy set up enhanced screening measures, including thermal cameras and medical staff at airports.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Update section |date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Italy medical cases chart}}\n\n===First confirmed cases===\nOn 31 January, the first two cases of COVID-19 were confirmed in [[Rome]]. A Chinese couple, originally from Wuhan, who had arrived in Italy on 23 January via [[Milan Malpensa Airport]], travelled from the airport to [[Verona]], then to Parma, arriving in Rome on 28 January. The next afternoon, they developed a cough, and by evening the man had a fever; the couple were taken to [[Lazzaro Spallanzani National Institute for Infectious Diseases]] where they tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 and were hospitalised.<ref name=\"prima\">{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_gennaio_31/virus-primi-due-casi-italia-due-cinesi-marito-moglie-italia-dieci-giorni-e365df1c-43b3-11ea-bdc8-faf1f56f19b7.shtml|title=Prima a Milano, poi l'hotel a Roma: le tappe dei 7 giorni di viaggio della coppia contagiata|last=Frignani|first=Rinaldo|date=2020-01-31|website=Corriere della Sera|language=it|access-date=2020-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\"Corriere_20Jan\"/> On 31 January, the Italian government suspended all flights to and from China and declared a state of emergency with the duration of six months. Prime Minister [[Giuseppe Conte]] said Italy was the first EU country to take this kind of precautionary measure.<ref name=\"thelocal-flight\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.it/20200131/italy-suspends-all-china-flights-after-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-in-rome/|title=Italy suspends all China flights as coronavirus cases confirmed in Rome|date=2020-01-31|website=THELOCAL|access-date=2020-02-26}}</ref> The government also introduced thermal scanners and temperature checks on international passengers arriving at Italian airports.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_04/coronavirus-controlli-gli-scanner-termici-aeroporti-italiani-c10b73d2-4796-11ea-bec1-6ac729c309c6.shtml|title=Coronavirus, controlli con gli scanner termici negli aeroporti italiani|last=Berberi|first=Leonard|date=2020-04-02|website=Corriere della Sera|language=it|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 February, an Italian repatriated from Wuhan tested positive for COVID-19, bringing the total number of cases in Italy to three.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-06-20-intl-hnk/index.html|title=February 6 coronavirus news|first1=Jessie |last1=Yeung |first2=Adam |last2=Renton |first3=Steve|last3=George|date=6 February 2020|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 February, the repatriated Italian recovered and was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.open.online/2020/02/22/coronavirus-bollettino-dello-spallanzani-guarito-il-ricercatore-italiano-verra-dimesso-oggi/|title=Coronavirus, bollettino dello Spallanzani: guarito il ricercatore italiano, verr\u00e0 dimesso oggi. Niccol\u00f2 \"sta benissimo\" \u2013 Il video|date=22 February 2020|website=Open|language=it-IT|access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref> On 22 and 26 February, the two previously infected Chinese tourists tested negative for COVID-19 at Lazzaro Spallanzani National Institute in Rome.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ilmessaggero.it/mondo/coronavirus_diretta_morti_contagi_oggi_ultime_notizie_26_febbraio_2020-5075865.html|title=Coronavirus, diretta. Contagi a quota 424, primo caso in Puglia, 12 morti. Lombardia, Fontana \u00e8 negativo, ma resta in isolamento per 14 giorni|website=www.ilmessaggero.it}}</ref>\n\n===Lombardy cluster===\nThe [[Lombardy]] outbreak came to light when a 38-year-old Italian tested positive in [[Codogno]], a [[comune]] in the [[province of Lodi]]. On 14 February, he felt unwell and went to a doctor in [[Castiglione d'Adda]]. He was prescribed treatments for influenza.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\" /> On 16 February, as the man's condition worsened, he went to Codogno Hospital, reporting respiratory problems.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\">{{Cite news |title=Codogno, i medici dell'ospedale in trincea: \"Quelle accuse del premier fanno pi\u00f9 male della malattia\"|language=Italian |publisher=la Repubblica |date=2020-02-26 |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/26/news/codogno_i_medici_dell_ospedale_in_trincea_quelle_accuse_del_premier_fanno_piu_male_della_malattia_-249593374/ |accessdate=2020-02-26}}</ref> Initially there was no suspicion of COVID-19, so no additional precautionary measures were taken, and the virus was able to infect other patients and health workers.<ref name=\"urlMailand:NZZ\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nzz.ch/international/mailand-coronavirus-epidemie-begann-in-spital-ld.1542330 |title=Mailand: Coronavirus-Epidemie begann in Spital |accessdate=24 February 2020 |website= www.nzz.ch (Neue Zurcher Zeitung)}}</ref> On 19 February, the wife of the patient revealed he had met an Italian friend who had returned from China on 21 January, who subsequently tested negative.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\" /> Later, the patient, his pregnant wife and a friend tested positive.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\" /> On 20 February, three more cases were confirmed after the patients reported symptoms of [[pneumonia]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus, primi tre contagi in Italia: 38enne, sua moglie e un amico in terapia intensiva. La donna insegna in un liceo |language=Italian |publisher=La Repubblica |url= https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/21/news/coronavirus_a_milano_contaggiato_38enne_e_un_italiano_ricoverato_a_codogno-249121707/?ref=RHPPTP-BH-I249146878-C12-P1-S1.12-T1 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |date=21 February 2020}}</ref> Thereafter, extensive screenings and checks were performed on everyone that had possibly been in contact with or near the infected subjects.<ref name=\"Messaggero_22Feb\">{{cite news |url= https://www.ilmessaggero.it/italia/coronavirus_diretta_lombardia_codogno_italiano_ultime_notizie-5064423.html |title=Coronavirus, diretta: morto uomo di 78 anni a Padova, \u00e8 la prima vittima italiana |website=Il Messaggero |date=22 February 2020 |accessdate=22 February 2020 |language=Italian}}</ref> It has been subsequently reported that the origin of these cases has a possible connection to the first European local transmission that occurred in [[Munich]], Germany, on 19 January 2020, consistent with phylogenetic analysis of viral genome.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Munich_Codogno\">{{cite news |last1=Luna |first1=Riccardo |title=Coronavirus: il paziente tedesco |url=https://rep.repubblica.it/pwa/generale/2020/03/05/news/coronavirus-250377117/ |accessdate=11 March 2020 |work=La Repubblica |date=5 March 2020 |language=it}}</ref><ref name=\"nextstrain\">{{cite web|url=https://nextstrain.org/ncov?dmax=2020-03-08&dmin=2019-12-15&fbclid=IwAR3UreH6NMoS8IjQqWOJpYdTX_Ygc5bW4gcBBf2gWe_QTDwxIL0oLMuwSgY|title=Genomic epidemiology of novel coronavirus (hCoV-19)| website=nextstrain.org|accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=pmid32003551>{{cite journal |last1=Rothe |first1=Camilla |last2=Schunk |first2=Mirjam |last3=Sothmann |first3=Peter |last4=Bretzel |first4=Gisela |last5=Froeschl |first5=Guenter |last6=Wallrauch |first6=Claudia |last7=Zimmer |first7=Thorbj\u00f6rn |last8=Thiel |first8=Verena |last9=Janke |first9=Christian |last10=Guggemos |first10=Wolfgang |last11=Seilmaier |first11=Michael |last12=Drosten |first12=Christian  |author-link12=Christian Drosten |last13=Vollmar |first13=Patrick |last14=Zwirglmaier |first14=Katrin |last15=Zange |first15=Sabine |last16=W\u00f6lfel |first16=Roman |last17=Hoelscher |first17=Michael |title=Transmission of 2019-nCoV Infection from an Asymptomatic Contact in Germany |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |date=5 March 2020 |volume=382 |issue=10 |pages=970\u2013971 |doi=10.1056/NEJMc2001468 |pmid=32003551 }}</ref> The 38-year-old man was asymptomatic for weeks, reportedly led an active social life and potentially interacted with dozens of people before spreading the virus at Codogno Hospital.<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\" /><ref name=\"urlMailand:NZZ\" /> Afterward, he was transferred to [[Policlinico San Matteo]] in [[Pavia]],<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.liberoquotidiano.it/news/italia/13566825/coronavirus-paziente-uno-codogno-trasferimento-pavia.html |title=Coronavirus, il 38enne paziente uno di Codogno trasferito nella notte a Pavia |website=liberoquotidiano.it |accessdate=2020-02-25}}</ref> and his wife to [[Ospedale Luigi Sacco|Sacco Hospital]] in Milan.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-25-20-hnk-intl/h_485832164169510b66e7bb07479c75b0 |title=Italian authorities identify first known patient to have caught coronavirus in Lombardy |first1=Helen |last1=Regan |first2=Adam |last2=Renton |date=2020-02-25 |website=CNN |accessdate=2020-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/25/news/coronavirus_paziente_1_ancora_grave_ma_stazionario_la_moglie_incinta_sta_bene-249550115/ |title=Coronavirus, \"paziente 1\" ancora grave ma stazionario, la moglie incinta sta bene |language=Italian |date=2020-02-25 |publisher=la Repubblica |accessdate=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Emergenza coronavirus (49496308758).jpg|thumb|upright=1.13|[[Protezione Civile|Civil Protection]] volunteers carrying out health checks at [[Guglielmo Marconi Airport]]]]\nOn 21 February 16 more cases were confirmed \u2013 14 in Lombardy, including the doctor who prescribed treatments to the 38-year-old Codogno man,<ref name=\"Repubblica_Codogno_doctors\" /> and two in [[Veneto]]. On 22 February, a 77-year-old woman from [[Casalpusterlengo]], who suffered from pneumonia and visited the same emergency room as the 38-year-old from Codogno, died in Lombardy.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/cronaca/lombardia/coronavirus-morta-una-donna-in-lombardia-seconda-vittima-italiana_15150431-202002a.shtml|title=Coronavirus, morta una donna in Lombardia: seconda vittima italiana |website=Tgcom24 |language=Italian |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref> Including the 78-year-old man who died in Veneto, the number of cases in Italy rose to 79.<ref name=\"CorrieredSera_76_recent_cases\" /><ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, in Veneto la prima vittima, Adriano Trevisan, 78 anni. Venti contagiati in Italia. Conte: \"Nuove misure\" |date=22 February 2020 |publisher=la Repubblica |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/22/news/cina_coronavirus_italia_virus_wuhan_influenza_codogno_lombardia_veneto_adriano_trevisan-249215365/}}</ref> Of the 76 newly discovered cases, 54 were found in Lombardy, including one patient in [[San Raffaele Hospital]] in Milan<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_22/coronavirus-italia-nuovi-contagi-lombardia-veneto-245e72d4-5540-11ea-8418-2150c9ca483e.shtml |title=Coronavirus, due casi a Milano |first=Simona |last=Ravizza |date=22 February 2020 |website=Corriere della Sera |language=Italian |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> and eight patients in [[Policlinico San Matteo]] in [[Pavia]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, a Pavia 8 pazienti ricoverati al San Matteo: anche una coppia di medici |language=Italian |website=Il Messaggero |date=2020-02-22 |url= https://www.ilmessaggero.it/italia/coronavirus_pavia_medici_contagiati_pieve_porto_morone_chignolo_po_cosa_sta_succedendo_22_febbraio_2020-5068178.html |accessdate=23 February 2020}}</ref> 17 in Veneto, two in [[Emilia-Romagna]], two in [[Lazio]] and one in [[Piedmont]].<ref>{{Cite news |first=Simona |last=Ravizza |title=Coronavirus, due casi a Milano |date=22 February 2020 |language=Italian |website=Corriere della Sera |url= https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_22/coronavirus-italia-nuovi-contagi-lombardia-veneto-245e72d4-5540-11ea-8418-2150c9ca483e.shtml |accessdate=22 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February, a 68-year-old woman with cancer from [[Trescore Cremasco]] died in [[Crema, Lombardy|Crema]]. The number of cases in Italy rose to 152, including fourteen patients being treated at Policlinico San Matteo in Pavia.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/23/news/coronavirus_italia-249329434/ |title=Coronavirus, terza vittima in Italia: \u00e8 una donna ricoverata a Crema. 152 casi positivi |date=23 February 2020 |website=la Repubblica |language=Italian |access-date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.globalist.it/news/2020/02/23/coronavirus-sale-a-14-il-numero-dei-casi-ricoverati-a-pavia-2053548.html |title=Coronavirus, sale a 14 il numero dei casi ricoverati a Pavia |publisher=globalist.it |language=Italian |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref> On 24 February, an 84-year-old man with pre-existing medical conditions from [[Villa di Serio]] died in [[Bergamo]] while hospitalised in the Papa Giovanni XXIII Hospital.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.huffingtonpost.it/entry/quarto-morto-in-italia-per-il-coronavirus-aveva-84-anni_it_5e5381b7c5b6b82aa65555f4 |title=Quarto morto in Italia per il coronavirus, aveva 84 anni |date=24 February 2020 |website=L'HuffPost |language=Italian |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref> An 88-year-old man from [[Caselle Landi]], who resided in Codogno, died on the same day.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.tgcom24.mediaset.it/cronaca/coronavirus-quarta-vittima-a-bergamo-in-lombardia-scoperti-150-casi_15242453-202002a.shtml |title=Coronavirus, in Italia si contano sei vittime e 230 contagi &#124; In Lombardia il numero maggiore dei casi |website=Tgcom24}}</ref><ref name=\"Repubblica_24Jan\" /> An 80-year-old man from [[Castiglione d\u2019Adda]] died at the Luigi Sacco Hospital in Milan. He was previously hospitalised in Lodi because of a heart attack, and then transferred to Milan when confirmed as positive.<ref name=\"Repubblica_24Jan\">{{Cite news |title=Coronavirus, sei morti in Italia, 229 contagi. Le vittime di oggi hanno tutte pi\u00f9 di 80 anni |language=Italian |website=la Repubblica |date=24 February 2020 |url= https://www.repubblica.it/cronaca/2020/02/24/news/coronavirus_149_i_casi_confermati_conte_i_contagi_possono_crescere_-249427098/ |accessdate=24 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ansa.it/canale_saluteebenessere/notizie/sanita/2020/02/24/coronavirus-_60aae600-8535-44d9-86de-48c4b71478ef.html |title=Coronavirus: sesta vittima in Italia, morto 80enne a Milano. Smentita dalla Regione Lombardia la morte della donna a Brescia - Salute & Benessere |date=22 February 2020 |website=ANSA.it}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.corriere.it/cronache/20_febbraio_24/coronavirus-chi-sono-vittime-italia-74e27360-56f6-11ea-b89d-a5ca249e9e1e.shtml |title=L'ex muratore , gli anziani ricoverati: chi sono le vittime |last=Del Frate |first=Claudio |date=24 February 2020 |website